---
import Base from "../layouts/Base.astro";
---

<Base title="About · LENS" active="about">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="eyebrow">About this site</div>
    <h1>A practice-centered guide, not an exhaustive one.</h1>

    <p>
      This site is a working reference for the emerging field of learning engineering.
      It's organized around the work itself — process, methods, tools, evidence, community —
      rather than around paper taxonomies or citation graphs. The goal is that someone
      arriving cold can quickly see what learning engineers are and what they do, and that
      practitioners can point colleagues here without a long preamble.
    </p>

    <h2>Sources &amp; relationship to lecommons</h2>
    <p>
      This site is deliberately small: it covers the JHU LENS program and the people and
      institutions directly tied to it. The broader learning-engineering corpus — the full
      reading list, tools, practice library, events calendar, and community roster, most of it
      curated from the <a href="https://sagroups.ieee.org/icicle/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">IEEE ICICLE</a>
      community — lives at the <a href="https://wrgr.github.io/lecommons/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Learning Engineering Commons</a>,
      which this site links to rather than duplicates. Named practitioners come from a separate
      study that catalogs people who self-apply the "Learning Engineer" title across LinkedIn,
      ResearchGate, Google Scholar, and institutional rosters; full methodology and caveats live
      in lecommons's <a href="https://github.com/wrgr/lecommons/blob/main/titlesearch/PROVENANCE.md" target="_blank" rel="noopener">provenance documentation</a>.
    </p>

    <h2>Scope &amp; caveats</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>Curated, not comprehensive — on purpose.</strong> This site stays focused on LENS;
        it doesn't try to be a complete index of the field. For that, see lecommons.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>English-language bias.</strong> Non-English title variants, older labels like
        "instructional designer," and government/defense practitioners who aren't publicly
        indexed are under-represented.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>ICICLE is authoritative.</strong> When ICICLE and this site differ on a
        definition or taxonomy, defer to ICICLE. This site doesn't claim to speak for IEEE
        ICICLE or host its content — it connects to it.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Links may rot.</strong> External resources change. File an issue if you find one.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Tools used</h2>
    <p>
      Claude (Anthropic) was used as an assistant throughout development and resource
      curation — for code generation, draft copy, and triage of the underlying corpus.
      Final editorial decisions, scope, and accuracy review are human-authored.
    </p>

    <h2>Contributing</h2>
    <p>
      Suggestions, corrections, and additional resources are welcome. Open an issue or PR in
      the repository. Editorial priorities: keep each section page short, each blurb under three
      sentences, and every inclusion tied to a real practice or community.
    </p>
  </div>
</Base>

<style>
  .container { padding-top: 3rem; }
  h1 {
    font-size: clamp(1.8rem, 4vw, 2.4rem);
    font-weight: 500;
    max-width: 32rem;
    margin-bottom: 2rem;
  }
  h2 {
    margin-top: 2.5rem;
    border-top: 1px solid var(--border);
    padding-top: 1.2rem;
    font-size: 1.15rem;
  }
  ul {
    padding-left: 1.3rem;
    max-width: var(--measure);
  }
  li {
    margin-bottom: .6rem;
    color: var(--ink-soft);
  }
  li strong { color: var(--ink); }
  code {
    font-family: var(--mono);
    font-size: .9em;
    background: var(--tint);
    padding: .08em .4em;
    border-radius: 2px;
  }
</style>
